# React Email Documentation

Use current React Email docs — do not rely on training data for API details.

## Priority 1: Context7 MCP

Use Context7 `query-docs` with library ID `/resend/react-email`.

Example queries:

- "Button Container Html Head Preview Text email template"
- "render plainText Tailwind send with Resend"
- "installation components import from react-email"

Workflow: search with the user's specific template or component need, then fetch the top 1–2 pages.

## Priority 2: Direct sources (shell fallback)

```bash
# Docs site
curl -s https://react.email/docs

# GitHub skill references (component list, sending patterns)
curl -s https://raw.githubusercontent.com/resend/react-email/canary/skills/react-email/references/COMPONENTS.md
curl -s https://raw.githubusercontent.com/resend/react-email/canary/skills/react-email/references/SENDING.md
```

## Conventions in this repo

- Email templates live in `apps/api/src/emails/` as `.tsx` files.
- Import components from `react-email` (`Html`, `Head`, `Body`, `Container`, `Text`, `Button`, `Preview`, etc.).
- Templates are rendered and sent via Resend from `apps/api/src/emails/` send helpers — see `resend-docs.mdc`.
- Use `react-jsx` (base `tsconfig`) for email templates; API `tsconfig` includes `src/**/*.tsx`.

## Notes

- React Email has no official docs MCP in this repo; Context7 is the primary path.
- Prefer table-based layouts and inline styles for email client compatibility.
- Always include `<Preview>` as the first child of `<Body>` for inbox preview text.
